# Case Study 1: SharePoint Oversharing Risk Assessment (Pre-Copilot)
 
## Objective
Build and document a realistic oversharing scenario in a Microsoft 365 tenant to
demonstrate the data-exposure risks that surface when Microsoft 365 Copilot is enabled.
 
## Environment
Microsoft 365 E5 (lab tenant) — SharePoint Online, Microsoft Entra ID, Microsoft Purview.
 
## What I did
1. Built a representative tenant with three SharePoint sites (HR-Confidential, Finance,
   General), 24 users, and dynamic security groups (department-based membership).
2. Created sensitive sample data (employee salaries + national IDs) in an Excel file.
3. Reproduced the three most common real-world oversharing patterns:
   - Shared a confidential file with an organization-wide link ("People in org can view").
   - Converted a site to Public, exposing it to every employee automatically.
   - Left sensitive data unclassified (no sensitivity labels).
 
## Key findings
- A single 30-second "Share" action exposed confidential salary data to the entire org.
- A Public site made sensitive content discoverable with no link required.
- No classification or protection existed on highly sensitive data.
 
## Why it matters
Microsoft 365 Copilot honors existing permissions exactly — so it instantly surfaces
overshared content in natural-language queries. These patterns represent the exact
risks Copilot exposes at rollout.
 
## Next steps (covered in follow-up case studies)
- Detect these risks using SharePoint Data Access Governance reports.
- Remediate with Sensitivity Labels, DLP, and Restricted Content Discovery.
 
## Skills demonstrated
Microsoft 365 administration, SharePoint sharing & permissions model, oversharing
risk identification, Copilot readiness fundamentals.
